Autobox recording device underneath summer roost of unknown bat species not long before sunrise. Sounds are heard (without time expansion) from the roost all hours of the day and sounds like swallows chattering. The roost is in an attic. In the night there are mainly two species occurring, soprano pipistrells and noctules. This is part of the same mystery as XC921595 and XC921593.

Could this be Nyctinomops laticaudatus? At the beginning of the recording there are faint S. bilineata pulses, but right at the end there are some pulses that I believe are from N. laticaudatus, it matches the shape and frequencies reported in the literature but it could overlap with the high frequency pulses of Molossus nigricans.
